column33: There are no regional variations of this policy.  An occupier of an outdoor place must not allow a gathering of more than 10 people to occur on, in or at a single undivided area of the place.  An occupier of an indoor place must not allow a gathering to occur on, in or at a single undivided area of the place if the gathering has more than 10 people; or the density of people present is more than one person per 4 square meters of the area.  Thus, it is assumed that public events are cancelled.  The following were exempt from these restrictions:  •	gathering of people who all live in the same residence  •	gathering for the purpose of conducting emergency services  •	residential facility  •	medical or health service facility  •	gathering for the purpose of maintaining normal activities in workplaces (e.g. schools, supermarkets, place of custody/detention, office building, hotel, etc. Details under COVID-19 Directions (No. 14) 2020: Directions for Gatherings)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220216012154/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/809953/cho-direction-14-gatherings.pdf

column115: On 19 June 2020, The Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) continued to emphasise the significant health risk of COVID-19 for the elderly and individuals with co-morbidities or low immunity. AHPPC updated and recommended that all Residential Aged Care Facilities (RACFs) ensured they were sufficiently prepared to manage a COVID-19 outbreak. Detailed guidance for facilities is available.  https://web.archive.org/web/20200621163846/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-update-to-residential-aged-care-facilities-about-minimising-the-impact-of-covid-19

The Australian government has specified Covid-19 advice for older people (aged 70 and above) on 14 May 2020. This includes general safety measures, assistance with food, online grocery ordering, & wellbeing support. Even though there is an easing in restrictions, in aged care facilities, some restrictions are remaining in place to protect older Australians. This includes: restricting visits, postponing large group visits & external excursions.    This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200701002614/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/advice-for-people-at-risk-of-coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-older-people

column115: On 10 June (published 19 June), the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) updated their advice for residential aged care facilities.  AHPPC recommends that Residential Aged Care facilities (RACFs) implement measures to reduce the risk of transmission to residents, including:  •	limiting visits to a maximum of two visitors at any one time per resident  •	visits should be conducted in a resident’s room, outdoors, or a specified area in the RACF, rather than communal areas with other residents  •	no large group visits should be permitted at this time, however gatherings of residents in communal or outdoor areas which adhere to social distancing and current jurisdictional requirements for gathering size may be permitted  AHPPC maintains that the following visitors and staff (including visiting workers) should not be permitted to enter a RACF:  •	Individuals who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days.  •	Individuals who have been in close contact with a confirmed case within the last 14 days.  •	Individuals who are unwell, particularly those with fever or acute respiratory infection (for example, cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath) symptoms.  •	Individuals who have not been vaccinated against influenza.  AHPPC recommends that:   •	children of all ages be permitted to enter RACFs  •	visiting service providers be permitted to enter RACFs when their services cannot be provided via telehealth or other adaptive models of care, and the resident cannot attend an external facility to receive these services  •	spouses or other close relatives or social supports are not limited in the number of hours that they spend with their spouse/relative  AHPPC recommends that facilities return to a higher level of protection (such as restricting visiting service providers) if there are recent cases of COVID-19 acquired in the local vicinity of the facility.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201201141832/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20200908041158/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-update-to-residential-aged-care-facilities-about-minimising-the-impact-of-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20201103111726/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/06/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-families-and-residents-on-restricted-visits-to-residential-aged-care-facilities.pdf

As of July 1st, 2020, the Australia government has specified Covid-19 advice for older people (aged 70 and above), this includes general safety measures, assistance with food, online grocery ordering, & wellbeing support.     And in terms of aged care facilities, although Australia is moving towards easing restrictions around the country, some restrictions will remain in place for aged care facilities to protect older Australians. This include: restricts visit, postpone large group visits & external excursions.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200701002614/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/advice-for-people-at-risk-of-coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-older-people    https://web.archive.org/web/20200630022809/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/advice-for-people-at-risk-of-coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-people-in-aged-care-facilities    Additional source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200714134151/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/06/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-families-and-residents-on-restricted-visits-to-residential-aged-care-facilities.pdf

Advice was provided on COVID-19 for older people by the federal government, actual policy restrictions were the responsibility of state/territory governments. Limitations on visitors were also in place during July 2020 to aged care homes. For example, people who had not had a flu vaccine in 2020 were not allowed to visit aged care facilities.  https://web.archive.org/web/20200630022809/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/advice-for-people-at-risk-of-coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-people-in-aged-care-facilities https://web.archive.org/web/20200701002614/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/advice-for-people-at-risk-of-coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-older-people

column69: This is a continuation of the existing policy that came into effect on 10 July with no regional variation.   Strict interstate border restriction is in place in Queensland as the State Government continues to move forward with re-opening the economy and recovery.     The COVID-19 border protection system now includes applications for a Border Declaration Pass which means a person who wishes to enter Queensland is required to obtain the Pass. People who have been in a COVID-19 hotspot within the last 14 days will no longer be able to quarantine in Queensland and will be turned away at our border, except people who need to be in Queensland for essential purposes and permitted reasons – these people will be required to quarantine in government provided accommodation at their expense.  Queensland residents who have been in a COVID-19 hotspot also can return home but will be required to quarantine for 14 days in government provided accommodation at their expense.    On 1 August, Greater Sydney is being declared a hotspot by the Queensland government, adding to the two other LGAs in NSW along with the whole state of Victoria that’s already been on the list.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220609030546/https://statements.qld.gov.au/statements/90178  https://web.archive.org/web/20220609030659/https://statements.qld.gov.au/statements/90188  https://web.archive.org/web/20220609030602/https://www.health.qld.gov.au/system-governance/legislation/cho-public-health-directions-under-expanded-public-health-act-powers/revoked/border-restrictions-9  https://web.archive.org/web/20220609030612/https://www.health.qld.gov.au/system-governance/legislation/cho-public-health-directions-under-expanded-public-health-act-powers/revoked/border-restrictions-8  https://web.archive.org/web/20200803152604/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/hotspots-covid-19

column115: According to the website of the Department of Health of the Australian Government (updated on 26 Jun, archived on 17 Aug), it suggests that special restrictions remain in place for aged care facilities to protect older Australians as of 15 Aug 2020. The document includes restrictions as follows.    The following people cannot enter residential aged care facilities:  -	People who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days  -	People who have been in contact with a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days  -	People who are unwell, including with a fever or symptoms of acute respiratory illness (e.g. cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath)  -	People who do not have an up-to-date (i.e. 2020) flu vaccination  Children of all ages can now visit RACFs. All visitors, including children, must follow any restrictions. This includes visitor numbers, physical distancing and personal hygiene. Facilities should not allow large group visits. Special consideration may be given to end-of-life situations, palliative care and dementia units.    Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advice on residential aged care facilities also sets out that residential aged care facilities should implement the following measures for restricting visits and visitors to reduce the risk of transmission to residents, including:  -	Limiting visits to a short duration;  -	Limiting visits to a maximum of two visitors at one time per day. These may be immediate social supports (family members, close friends) or professional service or advocacy;  -	Visits should be conducted in a resident’s room, outdoors, or in a specific area designated by the RACF, rather than communal areas where the risk of transmission to residents is greater;  -	No large group visits or gatherings, including social activities or entertainment, should be permitted at this time;  -	No school groups of any size should be allowed to visit RACFs.    Visitors should also be encouraged to practise social distancing practices where possible, including maintaining a distance of 1.5 metres.    This represents a level 2G policy.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200817232607/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20200919205923/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-families-and-residents-on-restricted-visits-to-residential-aged-care-facilities    https://web.archive.org/web/20200908043448/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-advice-on-residential-aged-care-facilities

According to the CDNA national guidelines for the prevention, control and public health management of COVID-19 outbreaks in residential care facilities in Australia (published by the Department of Health of the Australia Government on 13 Mar 2020, updated on 29 July 2020), it sets out restrictions on visitors and communal activities. It suggests that during a COVID-19 outbreak visitor access into and within the facility should be limited. Details include:    Facilities should implement the following:  -	suspend all group activities, particularly those that involve visitors (e.g. musicians).  -	postpone visits from non-essential external providers (e.g. hairdressers)  -	ask regular visitors and families of residents of the COVID-19 outbreak to only visit for essential reasons. Discourage visits by young children as they are generally unable to comply with standard precautions and PPE requirements. Record the name and phone number of visitors on a register. Screen any visitors for respiratory illness.  -	instruct visitors to          - wear PPE as directed by staff          - enter and leave the facility directly without spending time in communal areas          - perform good hand hygiene before entering and after leaving the resident’s room and the facility.    Additionally, visitors must be asked about symptoms and be instructed not to enter the RCF until any symptoms have resolved. In terms of isolation, a resident with relevant symptoms should be placed in a single room with their own ensuite facilities, if possible, while waiting for a diagnosis. Where possible, residents requiring droplet precautions should be restricted to their room. Residents may attend urgent medical or procedural appointments but should wear a surgical mask if tolerated. Staff escorting residents should wear a surgical mask, gowns, eye protection and gloves in addition to observing hand hygiene    The Guide to the Establishment of an Aged Care Health Emergency Response Operations Centre (published on 20 Aug 2020) is intended to operate alongside the CDNA national guidelines for the prevention, control and public health management of COVID-19 outbreaks in residential care facilities in Australia. It sets out that restricted people movement across facilities/suburbs/borders etc.    This represents a level 2G policy.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200923100917/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia    https://web.archive.org/web/20201103023506/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/07/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20210330035524/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre    https://web.archive.org/web/20210403145049/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/08/guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre-guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre.pdf

column33: As published in EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ACT 2005 (WA) Sections 71 and 72A CLOSURE AND RESTRICTION (LIMIT THE SPREAD) DIRECTIONS (NO 6) on 16 September 2020, there were capacity limits for stadium, events could proceed only with COVID Plans and regulations including 2 square metre rules. Music festivals were prohibited. The policy was implemented across WA. This came into effect at 11.59 p.m. on 26 June 2020.    This represents a loosening response to COVID-19 as outlined in The Closure and Restriction (Limit the Spread) Directions (No 4), made on 5 June 2020, that limited gatherings to 100 people. This policy was revised 16 September.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211207114625/https://www.wa.gov.au/system/files/2020-06/Closure%20and%20Restriction%20%28Limit%20the%20Spread%20%28Directions%29%20%28No%205%29.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20211207121515/https://www.wa.gov.au/system/files/2020-06/Revoked-Closure-and-Restriction-Limit-the-Spread-Directions-No-4.pdf
column42: As published in EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ACT 2005 (WA) Sections 71 and 72A CLOSURE AND RESTRICTION (LIMIT THE SPREAD) DIRECTIONS (NO 5), signed on 24th June, the following policies took affect:    - From 11.59 p.m. on 26 June 2020 gatherings of 2 or more patrons in a single undivided indoor space or a single undivided outdoor space at the place at the same time, where there is not at least 2 square metres of space for each patron at the gathering were not allowed  - Music festivals were banned  - Stadiums has capacity limits    This represents a relaxation of the policy response to CLOSURE AND RESTRICTION (LIMIT THE SPREAD) DIRECTIONS (N04), which limited gatherings to 100 people     This policy has since been revoked, on 16 September.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211207114625/https://www.wa.gov.au/system/files/2020-06/Closure%20and%20Restriction%20%28Limit%20the%20Spread%20%28Directions%29%20%28No%205%29.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20211207121515/https://www.wa.gov.au/system/files/2020-06/Revoked-Closure-and-Restriction-Limit-the-Spread-Directions-No-4.pdf

column77: On 10 September 2020, the Government of Western Australia, Department of Mines, Industry Regulation and Safety announced in a media statement that from 10 September the following would come into effect for the state of Western Australia:     A continuation of grants for 75 per cent of rent arrears, up to a maximum of $4,000, will be paid directly to eligible landlords. This includes any rent that was waived or reduced during the moratorium emergency period.     (Residential Rent Relief Grant Scheme)    This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.  This policy is current as of the 16th November 2021 and applications will be submitted until 31 December 2021    https://web.archive.org/web/20211116103959/https://www.commerce.wa.gov.au/announcements/covid-19-residential-rent-laws-extended-six-months    https://web.archive.org/web/20211116105319/https://www.commerce.wa.gov.au/consumer-protection/residential-rent-relief-grant-scheme

column15: According to the Department of Health (published on 17 April 2020), it provides that practical guidance and advice have been prepared for school leaders to engage with children, parents, teachers and support staff to reduce even further the relatively low risk of Coronavirus (COVID-19) transmission in schools during the COVID-19 pandemic. It suggests physical distancing. It also states that everyone must practise good hygiene to protect against infection and prevent the spread of COVID-19. Additionally, it also states to reduce the spread of viruses or germs in schools through environmental cleaning.    This represents a continuation of the policy of significant change to pre-covid times as of 15 Sep 2020.    See also Coronavirus (COVID-19) — Help stop the spread – resource for teachers and school staff published by the Department of Education, Skills and Employment (published on 29 May 2020).    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20210712060853/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-advice-on-reducing-the-potential-risk-of-covid-19-transmission-in-schools    https://web.archive.org/web/20210712143003/https://www.dese.gov.au/covid-19/resources/help-stop-spread-resource-teachers-and-school-staff
column51: According to the Department of Infrastructure, Transport, Regional Development and Communications (published on 29 May 2020), it states that public transport operators have continued to service the Australian community during the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic with risk mitigation and health and hygiene practices in place. It also states that compliance activities are a matter for the relevant jurisdiction. State and territory governments remain responsible for the operation of public transport services and jurisdictions will continue to provide guidance for their workforces and passengers.    Regarding relevant measures, it suggests that it is not recommended that PPE (such as gloves, eye protection and face masks) is routinely used outside of healthcare settings to protect against COVID-19. However, some members of the public may choose to wear a mask in situations where it is not feasible to maintain physical distancing e.g. on public transport and/or if they are at increased risk of severe illness if infected (e.g. because of their age or a chronic medical condition). This may provide some additional protection in these circumstances.    This represents a continuation of the policy of significant change to pre-covid times as of 15 Sep 2020.    Archived link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220118042123/https://www.infrastructure.gov.au/sites/default/files/migrated/transport/files/COVID19_public_transport_principles_29052020.pdf

column33: As published in EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ACT 2005 (WA) Sections 71 and 72A CLOSURE AND RESTRICTION (LIMIT THE SPREAD) DIRECTIONS (NO 6) on 16 September 2020, the following policies were in affect:    - Capacity limits for stadium  - Events could proceed with COVID Plans and capacity regulations  - Hospitality venues, and other listed venues, were limited to a 2 square metre rule. column42: As published in EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ACT 2005 (WA) Sections 71 and 72A CLOSURE AND RESTRICTION (LIMIT THE SPREAD) DIRECTIONS (NO 6), signed on 16th September 2020, the following policies took affect:    - From 3:50 p.m. on 16 September 2020 gatherings of 2 or more patrons in a single undivided indoor space or a single undivided outdoor space at the place at the same time, where there is not at least 2 square metres of space for each patron at the gathering were not allowed  - Events of over 500 allowed with a COVID plan  - Stadiums capacity limits increase    This represents a relaxation of the policy response to EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ACT 2005 (WA) Sections 71 and 72A CLOSURE AND RESTRICTION (LIMIT THE SPREAD) DIRECTIONS (NO 5), which prohibited music festivals. The 2 square metres rule is a continuation of previous policy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201002231856/https://www.wa.gov.au/sites/default/files/2020-09/Closure%20and%20Restriction%20%28Limit%20the%20Spread%29%20Directions%20%28No%206%29.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20211207114625/https://www.wa.gov.au/system/files/2020-06/Closure%20and%20Restriction%20%28Limit%20the%20Spread%20%28Directions%29%20%28No%205%29.pdf

column15: According to an Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) statement which was published on 25 February 2020, there was no evidence of any community transmission of COVID-19 in Australia and no reason for the general population to avoid public gatherings and restaurants or wear masks.  There was no mention of school closures or the implementation of COVID-safe measures in schools in AHPPC media releases between 1 and 7 March 2020. It is unlikely that specific COVID-safe policies were implemented in schools between this time, as a media statement published by the AHPPC on 6 March 2020 recommended that the Australian Government direct its primary focus towards containing COVID-19 domestically. Another media statement published by the AHPPC on 8 March 2020 stated that the risk of COVID-19 to the general Australian population was low, and that public events should proceed. column69: It is unlikely that the Australian Government mandated domestic travel restrictions during this time. There was no mention of such restrictions in the Chief Medical Officer's and Australian Minister for Health and Aged Care's press conference on 3 March, or the Deputy Chief Medical Officer's press conference on 7 March 2020, as the Australian Government focused their policy response on controlling international travel from areas heavily affected by COVID-19 (such as China, Iran, and South Korea).    The  Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) recommended that the Australian Government begin directing its primary focus towards containing COVID-19 domestically in a media statement published in 6 March 2020. In a media statement published on 8 March 2020, it also stated that the risk of COVID-19 to the general Australian population was low, with little need for social distancing measures at this time, indicating that there had not yet been a strong federal policy response to domestic travel.    The directions in place between 1-7 March 2020 were a continuation of existing restrictions. column74: According to a joint media release from the Australian Prime Minister, the Minister for Health, and the Minister for Foreign Affairs and Minister for Women, foreign nationals who had been in Iran on or after 1 March 2020 were prohibited from entering Australia for 14 days from the time they had left or transited through Iran. Australian citizens, permanent residents and immediate family members who had been in Iran in the past 14 days were required to quarantine at home for 14 days after arriving in Australia. This was a tightening of restrictions on individuals returning from Iran, making them consistent with existing travel restrictions placed on individuals returning from China. The first financial support payment offered by the Australian Government (the JobKeeper payment) commenced on 30 March 2020. column86: There were no dedicated campaigns designed to inform the public about COVID-19 or policy responses to COVID-19 between 1 and 7 March 2020 - the national campaign dedicated to informing the public about COVID-19 was launched on 14 March 2020.    The Australian Government did not urge Australians to be cautious of COVID-19 during this time. A media release published by the Minister for Health and the Chief Medical Officer on 2 March 2020 stated that it was perfectly safe for Australians to go about their regular business, and another media release published by the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) on 8 March 2020 stated that the risk of COVID-19 to the general Australian population was low.    This a continuation of existing messaging by the Australian Government.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200315022559/https://www.health.gov.au/news/launch-of-the-coronavirus-covid-19-campaign  https://web.archive.org/web/20220121011945/https:/parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22media%2Fpressrel%2F7218407%22  https://web.archive.org/web/20200414123541/https:/www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-coronavirus-covid-19-statement-on-8-march-2020-0
column88: According to a transcript of the Deputy Chief Medical Officer's press conference which was published on 7 March 2020, COVID-19 testing was recommended for travellers returning from countries considered to have a high or medium COVID-19 risk. However, testing was considered to be a clinical decision to be negotiated with an individual's doctor. Some States and Territories specifically advised individuals to speak with their doctors to discuss testing.    Other Australian Government media releases (such as one published on 3 March 2020) only mentioned COVID-19 testing for individuals who had returned from overseas or come into close contact with COVID-19 cases who had returned from overseas.    The limited testing availability in place was a continuation of existing measures.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220329040340/https://www.health.gov.au/news/deputy-chief-medical-officers-press-conference-about-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20210410144634/https://www.health.gov.au/news/chief-medical-officer-and-minister-hunts-joint-press-conference-on-coronavirus-covid-19
column90: Media releases and press conference transcripts released by the Australian Government during this time indicate that comprehensive contact tracing was likely in place.  For instance, a transcript of the Deputy Chief Medical Officer's press conference which was published on 7 March 2020 stated that all 70 patients of a doctor who tested positive to COVID-19 had been contacted by SMS.  A transcript of a press conference published by the Federal Chief Medical Officer and the Minister for Health on 29 February 2020 stated that Queensland Health had been conducting strict contact tracing measures and would ensure that COVID-19 cases in Queensland would be contacted.  A transcript of a press conference conducted by the Federal Chief Medical Officer and the Minister for Health and published on 3 March 2020 also provided a breakdown of the 29 COVID-19 cases within Australia at the time and their sources. Considering that there were only 74 diagnosed cases of COVID-19 in Australia as of 8 March 2020, it is likely that Australia had the capacity to conduct comprehensive contact tracing.    The measures in place between 1 and 7 March 2020 were a continuation of existing measures. column103: According to an Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) statement which was published on 25 February 2020, there was no evidence of any community transmission of COVID-19 in Australia and no reason for the general population to wear masks. A media release published by the Minister for Health and the Chief Medical Officer on 2 March 2020 stated that the best defenses against COVID-19 were good hand hygiene, cough and sneeze etiquette, and isolating when unwell, with no mention of mask-wearing. Another media release published by the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) on 8 March 2020 stated that the risk of COVID-19 to the general Australian population was low, with no need for social distancing measures and no mention of a need for mask-wearing. As such, it was highly unlikely that Australia imposed any mask mandates on the general population at this point in time. This was a continuation of existing directions. A media release published by the Minister for Health and the Chief Medical Officer on 2 March 2020 stated that it was perfectly safe for Australians to go about their regular business, and another media release published by the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) on 8 March 2020 stated that the risk of COVID-19 to the general Australian population was low, such that there was no need for social distancing measures. column74: According to a joint media released published by the Australian Minister for Health and the Chief Medical Officer published on 2 March 2020, healthcare and residential aged care workers arriving in Australia from Italy and South Korea were asked not to attend work for 14 days after arriving in Australia. This was an escalation of public health advice directed towards individuals arriving from Italy and South Korea.    Existing travel restrictions imposed on individuals arriving from China and Iran remained the same:  Foreign nationals who had been in Iran or China within the past 14 days were prohibited from entering Australia. Australian citizens, permanent residents and immediate family members who had been in Iran or China in the past 14 days were required to quarantine at home for 14 days after arriving in Australia.     Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220121004113/https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22media%2Fpressrel%2F7216775%22  https://web.archive.org/web/20220121011945/https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22media%2Fpressrel%2F7218407%22

According to a joint media release from the Australian Prime Minister, the Minister for Health, and the Minister for Foreign Affairs and Minister for Women, foreign nationals who had been in the Republic of Korea on or after 5 March 2020 were prohibited from entering Australia for 14 days from the time they had left or transited through Korea. Australian citizens, permanent residents and immediate family members who had been in Iran in the past 14 days were required to quarantine at home for 14 days after arriving in Australia.   Enhanced health screening and temperature checking arrangements were implemented for individuals arriving in Australia from Italy during this time.    This was a tightening of measures imposed on individuals arriving from the Republic of Korea and Italy. Existing travel restrictions imposed on individuals arriving from China and Iran remained the same:  Foreign nationals who had been in Iran or China within the past 14 days were prohibited from entering Australia. Australian citizens, permanent residents and immediate family members who had been in Iran or China in the past 14 days were required to quarantine at home for 14 days after arriving in Australia. column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, The Australian Government announced on 12 March 2020 that travel restrictions will continue to apply to travellers arriving from any part of mainland China, Iran, Republic of Korea and Italy.    Foreign nationals (excluding permanent residents of Australia) who have been in the following countries will not be allowed to enter Australia for 14 days from the time they have left or transited through:  mainland China  Iran  Republic of Korea  Italy.  Australian citizens and permanent residents will still be able to enter, as will their immediate family members (spouses, legal guardians or dependants only). They will be required to self-isolate at home for 14 days from the day they left China, Iran, the Republic of Korea or Italy.  Australia will deny entry to anyone who has left or transited a country subject to travel restrictions within the previous 14 days, with the exception of:  Australian citizens  permanent residents  New Zealand citizens resident in Australia  immediate family members of Australian citizens and permanent residents including spouses, minor dependants and legal guardians diplomats.  This represents a continuation of the policy response.  https://web.archive.org/web/20200314024611/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/news-media/current-alerts/novel-coronavirus
column77: According to a guide to the Australian Government COVID-19 disaster payments published on the Parliament of Australia website, there were no income support payments offered between 8 and 14 March 2020. column79: According to the Australian Financial Security Authority website and Australian Treasury website, there were no debt and contract relief measures in place between 8 and 14 March 2020. column86: There were no dedicated campaigns designed to inform the public about COVID-19 or policy responses to COVID-19 between 8 and 13 March 2020 - the national campaign dedicated to informing the public about COVID-19 was launched on 14 March 2020.    The Australian Government did not urge Australians to be cautious of COVID-19 during this time. A media release published by the Minister for Health and the Chief Medical Officer on 2 March 2020 stated that it was perfectly safe for Australians to go about their regular business, and another media release published by the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) on 8 March 2020 stated that the risk of COVID-19 to the general Australian population was low.    This represents continuation in the COVID-19 policy response.   https://web.archive.org/web/20200414123541/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-coronavirus-covid-19-statement-on-8-march-2020-0  https://web.archive.org/web/20220522143912/https://www.health.gov.au/news/letter-to-doctors-from-the-chief-medical-officer-about-the-response-to-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220522143916/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-coronavirus-covid-19-statement-on-11-march-2020-0  https://web.archive.org/web/20220522143924/https://www.health.gov.au/news/update-on-covid-19-from-the-chief-medical-officer  https://web.archive.org/web/20220522143929/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-coronavirus-covid-19-statement-on-13-march-2020-0
column88: According to the information published on the Department of Health website on 9 March 2020, Testing for COVID-19 infection is currently focused on those people with respiratory symptoms who have a relevant travel history or who have been in contact with cases.  Testing has largely been done so far by public health laboratories, but I am pleased to advise that we are working on further expanding access under Medicare to private pathology laboratories for the SARS CoV2 virus (COVID-19 virus). It is important at this time that all positive results are immediately reported to the state/territory public health unit, whose contacts are provided at the end of this letter.  However, when the national government has guidelines for what policies should happen, but the subnational jurisdiction sets substantive specifics that trigger changes in ordinal scale, and has direct say over implementation, we code NAT 0 (guidelines only).  This represents continuation in the COVID-19 policy response.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220522143912/https://www.health.gov.au/news/letter-to-doctors-from-the-chief-medical-officer-about-the-response-to-covid-19

There are no vaccines available in Australia until 22/02/2021  https://web.archive.org/web/20210218072330/https://www.health.gov.au/news/covid-19-vaccine-rollout-on-track-to-begin-22-february
column115: According to the website of the Australian National Government, they provide general advice on age care sector on 17 March 2020 and there are no recommendations or mandates on age care sector.   On 9 March 2020, the Communicable Diseases Network of Australian (CDNA) will soon be releasing guidelines for the prevention, control and management of COVID-19 in residential aged care facilities.   The Forum discussed the importance of and need for::  Aged care providers to:  Maintain their facility’s Infection Control protocols    Activate their facility’s COVID-19 Emergency Response Plan, including testing and updating assumptions in those plans  Finalise arrangements for seasonal flu vaccinations for residents, staff and volunteers  Communicate regularly with aged care consumers and their families  The Government to:  Clarify the role of aged care providers, state and territory governments and the Commonwealth in preparing for and responding to COVID-19  Ensure the availability of Personal Protective Equipment for aged care services  Giving consideration to increased delivery of infection control and procedures training    Ongoing communications including a forum focused on home and community care    Establish communications package directed at aged care workers, with practical advice on how to feel protected and prepared    Strategies to maintain and retain the workforce, and to develop options for an aged care surge workforce capacity which may involve the increasing the hours of visa holders, lifting regulatory arrangements around general practice and the use of graduates and students  A broad communications campaign for the community.  This represents continuation in the COVID-19 policy response.  https://web.archive.org/web/20200321051253/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-coronavirus-covid-19-statement-on-17-march-2020  https://web.archive.org/web/20200313042915/https://www.health.gov.au/ministers/senator-the-hon-richard-colbeck/media/statement-from-the-aged-care-covid-19-preparedness-forum

column88: On 20th of March 2020, according to the Australia's Department of Health, it was mentioned that doctor will tell you if you should be tested. The criteria being:  - You have returned from overseas in the past 14 days and you develop respiratory illness with or without fever  - You have been in close contact with a confirmed COVID-19 case in the past 14 days and you develop respiratory illness with or without fever  - You have severe community-acquired pneumonia and there is no clear cause  - You are a healthcare worker who works directly with patients and you have a respiratory illness and a fever    The rational for this is because there is a global shortage of the test kits that pathologists use to diagnose COVID-19. This is why we are doing targeted testing instead of widespread testing.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200321051456/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19

column115: As of 17th of March, according to the Australia's Department of Health, the Residential Aged Care Facilities are operating differently when compared to non-Covid period. This includes: limiting visits to a short duration, maximum of two visitors at one time per day, & no large group visits.    Visitors can't visit if:  - Those who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days.  - Those who have been in contact with a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days.  - Those with fever or symptoms of acute respiratory infection (e.g. cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath) symptoms.  - Those who have not been vaccinated against influenza (after 1st May 2020).    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200321051253/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-coronavirus-covid-19-statement-on-17-march-2020    Additional source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200414110933/https://www.health.gov.au/news/advice-for-aged-care-facilities-and-visitors-to-residents

column115: As of 13 April 2020, there continues to be narrow protections in place for elderly people across Australia. column69: The department of health stated that Australians must avoid all non-essential domestic travel. Australians should stay at home this Easter (12 April 2020) and not undertake holiday travel. column77: 1. The Government’s JobKeeper Payment helped keep more Australians in jobs and support businesses affected by the significant economic impact of the coronavirus. Under the JobKeeper Payment, workers would receive a fortnightly payment of $1,500 (before tax) through their employer. The JobKeeper Payment was open to eligible businesses, not-for-profits and the self-employed who can enrol at ato.gov.au. The Payment is available from 30 March 2020 until 27 September 2020 with employers receiving the first payments from the Australian Taxation Office (ATO) from the first week of May.   2. The Government was temporarily expanding eligibility to income support payments and establishing a new, time-limited Coronavirus supplement to be paid at a rate of $550 per fortnight.  This would be paid to both existing and new recipients of the JobSeeker Payment, Youth Allowance jobseeker, Parenting Payment, Farm Household Allowance and Special Benefit. The Coronavirus supplement will be paid for the next 6 months. Eligible income support recipients will receive the full amount of the $550 Coronavirus supplement on top of their payment each fortnight.  As a continuation of current policies, this was labelled as 2F. column88: The doctor would tell if someone should be tested then would arrange for the test. The testing criteria provided below were nationally agreed criteria. As the situation changes, states and territories may include additional criteria based on local needs.    Generally you will be tested if you develop fever or respiratory symptoms and meet at least one the following criteria:  -	you have returned from overseas in the past 14 days  -	you have been in close contact with someone diagnosed with COVID-19 in the past 14 days  -	you travelled on a cruise ship (either passenger or crew) in the 14 days before developing symptoms  -	you are a health care, aged care or residential care worker  -	you have lived in an area where there is a higher risk of community transmission, as defined by the local public health unit    You should also be tested if you meet all of the following criteria:   -	you are in hospital  -	you have fever and serious respiratory symptoms  -	there is no other clear cause of the symptoms    People in high-risk settings will be tested if there are 2 or more people with fever and respiratory symptoms in the setting. High-risk settings include:   -	aged and residential care facilities  -	detention centres or correctional facilities  -	boarding schools  -	military bases (including navy ships) that have live-in accommodation  -	rural and remote Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities  https://web.archive.org/web/20200420032916/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19

According to ‘Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advice on reducing the potential risk of COVID-19 transmission in schools (24 April 2020)’ (published on 26 April 2020), schools need to practise physical distancing to slow the spread of COVID-19. Everyone must practise good hygiene to protect against infection and prevent the spread of COVID-19. Schools would also need to conduct significant cleaning:  -	clean and disinfect frequently used high-touch surfaces such as benchtops, desks, doorknobs, taps, and hand rails at regular intervals throughout the day with a detergent solution or detergent/disinfectant wipes  -	clean and disinfect frequently used objects such as computers, photocopiers and sports equipment with detergent solution or detergent/disinfectant wipes  -	in those jurisdictions where students are allowed to have mobile phones, schools should restrict access to mobile phones during the school day. Schools and jurisdictions can have the flexibility to make their own procedures around how to do this  -	clean and disinfect any play equipment that has not been closed at the end of each recess and the end of the day  -	increase the amount of fresh air available indoors by opening windows or adjusting air conditioning  -	provide bins in every classroom for used tissues, and empty them regularly throughout the day  -	clean frequently touched points in the bathrooms after each recess and at the end of the day    This represents a 1G level of policy as of 27 April 2020 in Australia. column77: According to the Treasury, the JobKeeper Payment became available introduced from 30 March 2020 until 27 September 2020.    The JobKeeper Payment is a payment made to eligible businesses and not-for-profits affected by the Coronavirus to support them in retaining employees. Businesses must have paid their employees before they are entitled to receive the JobKeeper payment.     Where an employee’s total remuneration is less than $1,500 per fortnight (before tax), or has been stood down, the employer must provide the employee at least $1,500 per fortnight (before tax). Where an employee earns more than $1,500 per fortnight, employers can use the payment to subsidise the employee’s wages.    Self-employed individuals will also be eligible to receive the JobKeeper payment. Self-employed individuals are not informal workers as they operate their own business with an ABN in order to be eligible to the JobKeeper Payment. Therefore, this scheme was available to formal workers.    This represents a 2F level of policy as of 27 April 2020 in Australia.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304125206/https://treasury.gov.au/sites/default/files/2020-04/JobKeeper_frequently_asked_questions_2.pdf

column88: The Department of Health provided nationally agreed testing criteria. As the situation changes, states and territories may include additional criteria based on local needs.    Generally, people will be tested if they develop fever or respiratory symptoms and meet at least one the following criteria:  -	they have returned from overseas in the past 14 days  -	they have been in close contact with someone diagnosed with COVID-19 in the past 14 days  -	they travelled on a cruise ship (either passenger or crew) in the 14 days before developing symptoms  -	they are a health care, aged care or residential care worker  -	they have lived in an area where there is a higher risk of community transmission, as defined by the local public health unit    They should also be tested if you meet all of the following criteria:   -	they are in hospital  -	they have fever and serious respiratory symptoms  -	there is no other clear cause of the symptoms    People in high-risk settings will be tested if there are 2 or more people with fever and respiratory symptoms in the setting.    High-risk settings include:   -	aged and residential care facilities  -	detention centres or correctional facilities  -	boarding schools  -	military bases (including navy ships) that have live-in accommodation  -	rural and remote Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities    This represents a 1 level of policy as of 27 April 2020 in Australia.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200428020753/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19

column115: ‘Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advice on residential aged care facilities’ (published on 21 April 2020; archived on 27 April 2020) sets out recommendations to Residential Aged Care Facilities (RACFs) to prevent introduction of COVID-19 into their facility.    In relation to visitors, it suggests that RACFs should implement the following measures for restricting visits and visitors to reduce the risk of transmission to residents, including:  -	Limiting visits to a short duration;  -	Limiting visits to a maximum of two visitors at one time per day. These may be immediate social supports (family members, close friends) or professional service or advocacy;  -	Visits should be conducted in a resident’s room, outdoors, or in a specific area designated by the RACF, rather than communal areas where the risk of transmission to residents is greater;  -	No large group visits or gatherings, including social activities or entertainment, should be permitted at this time;  -	No school groups of any size should be allowed to visit RACFs.    Visitors should also be encouraged to practise social distancing practices where possible, including maintaining a distance of 1.5 metres.    Children aged 16 years or less must be permitted to visit only by exception, as they are generally unable to comply with hygiene measures. Exemptions can be assessed on a case-by-case basis, for example, where the resident is in palliative care.    Measures such as phone or video calls must be accessible to all residents to enable more regular communication with family members. Family and friends should be encouraged to maintain contact with residents by phone and other social communication apps, as appropriate.    In relation to residents, it suggests active screening for symptoms of COVID-19 in residents being admitted or re-admitted from other health facilities and community settings should be conducted. No new residents with COVID-19 compatible symptoms are permitted to enter the facility.    Residents admitted from other health facilities should be assessed by appropriate medical staff prior to admission to the facility.    Appropriate infection prevention practices should be implemented for residents returning from treatment or care at other facilities.    In particular, no external excursions for residents should currently be permitted. This is extensive protection.    This represents a 3G level of policy as of 27 April 2020 in Australia.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200427071655/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-advice-on-residential-aged-care-facilities

column24: This is a continuation of the existing policy first introduced in early May.   On 8 May, the National cabinet put forward the three-step framework to gradually remove baseline restrictions to enable Australian to live in a Covid-19 safe economy. Individual states and territories will determine the timeframe for graduating between steps and individual restrictions to remove. This reflects the fact that states and territories are at different stages of the pandemic response.  For each of the major areas of restrictions the national government have set out three key steps:   •	Step 1 will focus on carefully reopening the economy, and giving Australians opportunities to return to work and social activities, including gatherings of up to 10 people, up to 5 visitors in the family home and some local and regional travel  •	Step 2 builds on this with gatherings of up to 20, and more businesses reopening, including gyms, beauty services and entertainment venues like galleries and cinemas.  •	Step 3 will see a transition to COVID safe ways of living and working, with gatherings of up to 100 people permitted. Arrangements under step 3 will be the ‘new normal’ while the virus remains a threat. International travel and mass gatherings over 100 people will remain restricted.    The AHPPC provides advice on the conditions that must be met by businesses to reopen in the safest possible way while living with covid-19.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220514065447/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-08may20  https://web.archive.org/web/20220514111729/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-050520

One of the policies included in the easing of baseline restrictions is regarding mass gathering. Gathering of up to 100 people is permitted in Step 3 process of transition to Covid safe ways of living and working. Arrangements under this step 3 will be the ‘new normal’ while the virus remains a threat. column60: This is a continuation of the existing policy.   On 8 May, the national cabinet introduced the three-step plan that provides a pathway for jurisdictions to move towards COVID safe communities in a way that best suits their individual circumstances. States and territories are able to move between the steps on the pathway at different times, in line with their current public health situation and local conditions.     The plan is the step towards the re-opening of the economy in the safest possible way while living with covid-19. With this, many Australians can start getting out to the shops, undertaking some local trips and travel, visiting playgrounds and public parks, and having friends and family around with a bit more freedom – up to 5 visitors in the family home is permitted in Step 1.    The national government highlights the importance of people to stay home when unwell, to be able to move forward with this reopening steps.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220514065447/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-08may20
column69: On 8 May (a continuation of the existing policy), the national cabinet introduced the three-step plan that provides a pathway for jurisdictions to move towards COVID safe communities in a way that best suits their individual circumstances. States and territories are able to move between the steps on the pathway at different times, in line with their current public health situation and local conditions. This is the first policy of this kind since the covid-19 pandemic hit Australia.   With this policy, Australian can start undertaking some local trips and travel – some jurisdictions may choose to maintain interstate travel restrictions.  Additionally, on 15 May, National Cabinet agrees to a framework to inform decision around lifting remote area travel restrictions as the country plan to move through the three-step plan for a CovidSafe Australia. column115: On 21 April (the continuation of the existing policy), the National Cabinet reconfirmed the principles announced on 18 March 2020 regarding visits to aged care facilities. In line with these principles, visits should be limited to a short duration, a maximum of two visitors at one time per day, and conducted in line with social distancing practices.   Infection prevention and control measures must be balanced against the needs and best interests of residents. Aged care providers are best placed to make these assessments on a case by case basis.  National Cabinet also reiterated that the following visitors and staff (including visiting workers) should not be permitted to enter the aged care facilities:  •	Those who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days;  •	Those who have been in contact with a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days;  •	Those with fever or any (even mild) symptoms of acute respiratory infection (e.g. cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath); and  •	Those who have not been vaccinated against influenza (after 1 May).  see: https://web.archive.org/web/20220515000643/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-210420    Additionally, on 24 April, the National government stressed that the AHPPC advice that it is not acceptable for any facility to put in place restrictions beyond the principles agreed on 17 March 2020. These include complete lockdowns or banning all visits from carers and families, other than during a specified facility outbreak.  Facilities need to know the appropriate levels of infection control and prevention to implement, in consultation with the relevant public health units and the Aged Care Quality and Safety Commission. The Commonwealth Government will continue to monitor the situation and will take steps, if necessary, to require facilities to seek an exemption from the Commission before implementing additional restrictions.  See: https://web.archive.org/web/20220515000647/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-24april20    Lastly, on 1 May, the Morrison government announces the additional covid-19 specific support packaging totalling $205 million under targeted measures. The support is aimed at ensuring aged care providers can offer reinforced levels of safety and care for those who need it most. Endorsement of the ‘Code of Conduct on Pandemic Procedures’ draft for residential aged care is made by the National cabinet in order to drive a more responsive and consistent approach to visitation and communication across residential aged care.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220512035907/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/new-covid-19-payment-keep-senior-australians-residential-aged-care-safe  https://web.archive.org/web/20220512034531/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-1may20

column15: This is a continuation of the existing policy introduced in April.   The national cabinet advises that schools can be fully open but need to adhere to the practical guidance and advice provided by AHPPC to provide a safe environment for students/staff and reduce the risk of transmission in school.   The National Principles for School education provided by the national cabinet include:  1.	It is accepted that during the COVID-19 crisis, alternative flexible, remote delivery of education services may be needed  2.	State and Territory Governments and non-government sector authorities are responsible for managing and making operational decisions for their school systems respectively, subject to compliance with relevant funding agreements with the Commonwealth.    University and other higher education also can continue operating with risk mitigation measures including working from home arrangements where effective.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220514040746/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-160420  https://web.archive.org/web/20220514041354/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures
column24: This is a continuation of the existing policy first introduced on 8 May.   The national government implements the 3-step plan that provides a pathway for jurisdictions to move towards COVID safe communities in a way that best suits their individual circumstances. States and territories are able to move between the steps on the pathway at different times, in line with their current public health situation and local conditions.   For each of the major areas of restrictions the national government have set out three key steps:   •	Step 1 will focus on carefully reopening the economy, and giving Australians opportunities to return to work and social activities, including gatherings of up to 10 people, up to 5 visitors in the family home and some local and regional travel  •	Step 2 builds on this with gatherings of up to 20, and more businesses reopening, including gyms, beauty services and entertainment venues like galleries and cinemas.  •	Step 3 will see a transition to COVID safe ways of living and working, with gatherings of up to 100 people permitted. Arrangements under step 3 will be the ‘new normal’ while the virus remains a threat. International travel and mass gatherings over 100 people will remain restricted.  As states and territories are at different stages of the pandemic response, each of individual state and territory will determine the timeframe for graduating between steps and individual restrictions to remove based on evidence of increases in transmission or outbreaks, increased pressure on the health system, testing and personal protective equipment demand, demand on the public health response to cases and community adherence and acceptance of these measures. For this reason, the policy for this indicator is interpreted as 0.   The AHPPC provides advice on the conditions that must be met by businesses to reopen in the safest possible way while living with covid-19.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220514065447/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-08may20  https://web.archive.org/web/20220517053800/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-following-national-cabinet-meeting  https://web.archive.org/web/20220517061732/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-12june20

column51: On 29 May (a continuation of the existing policy), the National cabinet released a statement that public transport services are the responsibility of the states and territories – hence policy coded as 0.    In the announcement, National Cabinet also endorsed principles approved by the AHPPC which will help manage the health and safety of workers and passengers on public transport networks.  The principles outline the responsibility passengers must take when traveling on public transport including not travelling when feeling unwell, maintaining physical distance from drivers and other passengers, and avoiding handling cash.  Under the principles, public transport users are not required to wear masks but may do so on a voluntary basis.  The principles should be considered alongside Work Health and Safety requirements, public health advice and other advice jurisdictions provide in relation to mass gatherings, including on public transport.  National Cabinet agreed that the principles will be reviewed as governments progress through the three-step plan to take into account any emerging challenges or innovative solutions, or as interactions with international travel start to be considered.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220517053800/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-following-national-cabinet-meeting

column88: This is a continuation of the existing policy.  As published on the DoH website (last updated on 11 June), those that have cold or flu like symptoms, such as a cough, fever, sore throat, shortness of breath or runny nose, even if these are mild, should get tested by attending a free COVID-19 respiratory clinic or contact your doctor and they will arrange the test, this may attract a fee.   Testing is important for anyone with symptoms and particularly if any of the following apply to you:  •	you have returned from overseas in the past 14 days  •	you travelled on a cruise ship (either passenger or crew) in the 14 days before developing symptoms  •	you have been in close contact with someone diagnosed with COVID-19 in the past 14 days  •	you are a health care, aged care or residential care worker or staff member with direct patient contact  •	you have lived in or travelled through an area where there is a higher risk of community transmission, as defined by the local public health unit  People in high-risk settings (e.g., aged & residential care facilities, rural and remote communities) will be regularly monitored to ensure symptoms are identified earlier. Rapid response plans will be activated if someone in those settings develops a fever or respiratory symptoms. People who have recovered from COVID-19 need to be tested before they can go into high-risk settings.    States and territories may adjust their testing criteria based on local needs, therefore, the NAT level policy is coded as 0.     https://web.archive.org/web/20200629073633/www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19

column115: This is a continuation of the existing policy commenced in April.   The national government agreed that visits in aged care facilities should be limited to a short duration, a maximum of two visitors at one time per day, and conducted in line with social distancing practices.   Infection prevention and control measures must be balanced against the needs and best interests of residents. Aged care providers are best placed to make these assessments on a case by case basis.  The following visitors and staff (including visiting workers) should not be permitted to enter the aged care facilities:  •	Those who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days;  •	Those who have been in contact with a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days;  •	Those with fever or any (even mild) symptoms of acute respiratory infection (e.g. cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath); and  •	Those who have not been vaccinated against influenza (after 1 May).     The national government stressed that it is not acceptable for any facility to put in place restrictions beyond the principles agreed. These include complete lockdowns or banning all visits from carers and families, other than during a specified facility outbreak.     Facilities need to know the appropriate levels of infection control and prevention to implement, in consultation with the relevant public health units and the Aged Care Quality and Safety Commission. The Commonwealth Government will continue to monitor the situation and will take steps, if necessary, to require facilities to seek an exemption from the Commission before implementing additional restrictions.    Additionally, on 1 May, the Morrison government announces the additional covid-19 specific support packaging totalling $205 million under targeted measures. The support is aimed at ensuring aged care providers can offer reinforced levels of safety and care for those who need it most. Endorsement of ‘Code of Conduct on Pandemic Procedures’ draft for residential aged care is made by the National cabinet in order to drive a more responsive and consistent approach to visitation and communication across residential aged care.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220512035907/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/new-covid-19-payment-keep-senior-australians-residential-aged-care-safe  https://web.archive.org/web/20220512034531/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-1may20  https://web.archive.org/web/20220515000647/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-24april20  https://web.archive.org/web/20220515000643/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-210420

column33: On 12 June, the national government presents a new policy to further ease the gathering restriction as government continue to expect the 3-step framework for covid-safe Australia to be completed in July 2020.  Outdoor events including stadiums are now permitted with up to 40,000 spectator capacity, ticketed and seated events will be able to be held in front of a crowd of no more than 25% of capacity under Step 3. These events are subject to a Covid-Safe measures and arrangements (e.g., 1 person per 4sqm, staying 1.5 meters apart from each other whenever possible etc). However, high-risk outdoor events without ticketed seating such as music festivals do not form part of this Step 3 and it will be considered following further advice from medical experts.   For outdoor venues of more than 40,000 spectator capacity, further advice is being sought from the AHPPC, with arrangements to be settled by the states and territories on a venue by venue basis.    The National government also makes a statement on the high risk of covid-19 infections in attending mass gathering protests due to large numbers of people closely gathering and challenges in identifying all contacts. Therefore, urging people to not participate.     As states and territories are at different stages of the pandemic response, each of individual state and territory will determine when to move to the Step 3 framework based on their current public health situation and local conditions. For this reason, the NAT level policy is coded as 0 (guidelines only).       https://web.archive.org/web/20220517061732/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-12june20
column42: On 12 June, the national government agrees to remove the 100 person limit on non-essential indoor gatherings under the Step 3 Framework and replace it with covid-safe measures such as 1 person per 4sqm, staying 1.5 meters away from other people whenever possible, staying home when unwell and getting tested if you have respiratory symptoms or a fever; developing Covidsafe plan for workplace and premises.   National Cabinet reiterated that high risk venues such as nightclubs do not form part of Step 3 and will be considered following further advice from medical experts.    As for outdoor events including stadiums, up to 40,000 spectator capacity, ticketed and seated events will be able to be held in front of a crowd of no more than 25 per cent of capacity under Step 3.  At a minimum, COVID-Safe arrangements must be maintained including: 1 person per 4sqm, staying 1.5 metres away from other people whenever and wherever possible, Maintaining good hand washing and cough/sneeze hygiene,staying home when unwell, and getting tested if you have respiratory symptoms or a fever, downloading the COVIDSafe app to allow identification and traceability of people that have been in contact with a confirmed COVID case.  National Cabinet reiterated that high-risk outdoor events without ticketed seating such as music festivals do not form part of Step 3 and will be considered following further advice from medical experts.  This represents a further relaxation of the gathering policy as the government continue to expect the 3-step framework for covid-safe Australia to be completed in July 2020.    States and territories will determine when to implement these changes under Step 3 based on their individual public health situation and local conditions. For this reason, this policy is interpreted as 0.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220517061732/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-12june20

column115: Residential aged care facilities were legally responsible for infection prevention and control under the Aged Care Act 1997 and the Aged Care Quality Standards.  You must:  -	manage visitor and entry restrictions, including for new and returning residents.  -	monitor the health of your staff.  -	prevent and control infections.  -	put up signs and remind visitors of the steps they need to take to help protect residents, including their flu vaccination.  -	ensure all visitors comply with the Aged Care Visitor Access Code.  -	manage any COVID-19 outbreaks and follow the COVID-19 outbreak guidelines.    In the COVID-19 Infection Prevention and Control for Residential Care Facilities updated on 17 May 2020, there were visitor restriction and signage:  • Ensure that all visitors, including essential external providers and visitors to residents:  o Visit only one resident (or essential staff member).  o Go directly to the resident’s room or area designated by the Residential Care Facilities (RFC), and avoid communal areas.  o Maintain separation of 1.5 metres from residents, if possible.  o Use alcohol-based hand rub or wash their hands before entering and on leaving the RCF and the resident’s room.  o Practice cough etiquette/respiratory hygiene.  o If visiting a resident who is in isolation or quarantine, observe contact and droplet precautions, as directed by RCF staff.  • Screen visitors on entry to the facility for epidemiological (recent travel, contact with a COVID-19 case) and clinical risk factors (acute respiratory infection).  Website about Providing aged care services during COVID-19: https://web.archive.org/web/20200618105452/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-the-health-and-aged-care-sector/providing-aged-care-services-during-covid-19  COVID-19 Infection Prevention and Control for Residential Care Facilities (MAY 16, 2020): https://web.archive.org/web/20200527204540/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/05/coronavirus-covid-19-guidelines-for-infection-prevention-and-control-in-residential-care-facilities_0.pdf

column115: On 10 June (published 19 June), the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) updated their advice for residential aged care facilities.  AHPPC recommends that Residential Aged Care facilities (RACFs) implement measures to reduce the risk of transmission to residents, including:  •	limiting visits to a maximum of two visitors at any one time per resident  •	visits should be conducted in a resident’s room, outdoors, or a specified area in the RACF, rather than communal areas with other residents  •	no large group visits should be permitted at this time, however gatherings of residents in communal or outdoor areas which adhere to social distancing and current jurisdictional requirements for gathering size may be permitted  AHPPC maintains that the following visitors and staff (including visiting workers) should not be permitted to enter a RACF:  •	Individuals who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days.  •	Individuals who have been in close contact with a confirmed case within the last 14 days.  •	Individuals who are unwell, particularly those with fever or acute respiratory infection (for example, cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath) symptoms.  •	Individuals who have not been vaccinated against influenza.  AHPPC recommends that:   •	children of all ages be permitted to enter RACFs  •	visiting service providers be permitted to enter RACFs when their services cannot be provided via telehealth or other adaptive models of care, and the resident cannot attend an external facility to receive these services  •	spouses or other close relatives or social supports are not limited in the number of hours that they spend with their spouse/relative  AHPPC recommends that facilities return to a higher level of protection (such as restricting visiting service providers) if there are recent cases of COVID-19 acquired in the local vicinity of the facility.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201201141832/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20200908041158/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-update-to-residential-aged-care-facilities-about-minimising-the-impact-of-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20201103111726/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/06/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-families-and-residents-on-restricted-visits-to-residential-aged-care-facilities.pdf

column33: As of July 8th, 2020, according to the Sydney Morning Herald, the Federal government provided some guideline on what sort of restrictions public events should have, which meant that public events can still be held. However, noting that it is still up to the states and territories governments to decide the restrictions on public events.    From the article, it was mentioned that, except for Victoria (which was under lockdown during this period), the national rules say venues can now shelve specific capacity limits and instead just follow the rule that there must be four square metres of space per person. Venues with 40,000 seats or less must stay below 25 per cent of their usual capacity and those with more than 40,000 seats cannot have more than 10,000 people. Seat allocation must keep the golden 1.5-metre rule of social distancing in place between all patrons.    But beyond these revised rules, how states are choosing to reopen varies wildly on the ground. column33: While ultimately state and territory governments have control over restrictions on public events, the federal government made some recommendations via guidelines for what these restrictions should look like. They encouraged venues with less than 40 000 seats to stay below 25% of usual capacity, and those with over 40 000 seats to only have 10 000 people. And seat allocation was advised to keep 1.5m between patrons. State-by-state implementation of these recommendations varied widely. https://web.archive.org/web/20200630150129/https://www.smh.com.au/national/covid-19-what-are-the-public-health-rules-now-20200511-p54rux.html

column77: Median weekly earnings were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the JobKeeper Payment was greater than 50% median salary.  The JobKeeper Payment helps businesses significantly impacted by the Coronavirus cover the costs of their employees’ wages, so more Australians can retain their jobs and continue to earn an income. Employers will notify employees if they are claiming the fortnightly payment of $1,500. The first payments were made in the week commencing 4 May 2020.  Since 27 April 2020 the Government has temporarily expanded eligibility to income support payments and established a new, time-limited Coronavirus supplement to be paid at a rate of $550 per fortnight. This is paid to both existing and new recipients of Jobseeker Payment, Youth Allowance, Parenting Payment, Austudy, ABSTUDY Living Allowance, Farm Household Allowance and Special Benefit. The Government is also temporarily expanding access for the JobSeeker Payment by relaxing the partner income test.  This represents continuation in the COVID-19 policy response.   https://web.archive.org/web/20210714153920/https://treasury.gov.au/sites/default/files/2020-07/Fact_sheet-Income_Support_for_Individuals.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220331122605/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings-and-hours-australia/may-2021
