column51: According to the Department of Infrastructure, Transport, Regional Development and Communications (published on 29 May 2020), it states that public transport operators have continued to service the Australian community during the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic with risk mitigation and health and hygiene practices in place. It also states that compliance activities are a matter for the relevant jurisdiction. State and territory governments remain responsible for the operation of public transport services and jurisdictions will continue to provide guidance for their workforces and passengers.    Regarding relevant measures, it suggests that it is not recommended that PPE (such as gloves, eye protection and face masks) is routinely used outside of healthcare settings to protect against COVID-19. However, some members of the public may choose to wear a mask in situations where it is not feasible to maintain physical distancing e.g. on public transport and/or if they are at increased risk of severe illness if infected (e.g. because of their age or a chronic medical condition). This may provide some additional protection in these circumstances.    This represents a continuation of the policy of significant change to pre-covid times as of 15 Aug 2020. column88: According to the Australian Government (published on 7 August 2020), it states that advice if people have cold or flu like symptoms, they should seek medical advice about having a test for COVID-19. If people have a fever, cough, sore throat or shortness of breath, it is important they get tested.    Additionally, testing is even more important if people are unwell and:  -	people have recently returned to Australia from overseas. All travellers will be quarantined for 14 days on arrival into Australia;  -	people have been in close contact with someone diagnosed with COVID-19 in the past 14 days;  -	people are a health care, aged care or residential care worker or staff member with direct patient contact.    People will be able to contact their doctor to arrange a test or they can attend a respiratory clinic.    This suggests that people will likely be able to get tested if they have symptoms and meet specific criteria as stated above.    Archived link: https://web.archive.org/web/20211114013408/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/08/testing-for-covid-19.pdf
column90: According to the Australian Government (updated on 4 Aug 2020, archived on 15 Aug 2020), the COVIDSafe app has been introduced to help state and territory health officials to quickly identify and contact people who may have been exposed to COVID-19 (called ‘close contacts’) as of 15 Aug 2020. column115: According to the website of the Department of Health of the Australian Government (updated on 26 Jun, archived on 17 Aug), it suggests that special restrictions remain in place for aged care facilities to protect older Australians as of 15 Aug 2020. The document includes restrictions as follows.    The following people cannot enter residential aged care facilities:  -	People who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days  -	People who have been in contact with a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days  -	People who are unwell, including with a fever or symptoms of acute respiratory illness (e.g. cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath)  -	People who do not have an up-to-date (i.e. 2020) flu vaccination  Children of all ages can now visit RACFs. All visitors, including children, must follow any restrictions. This includes visitor numbers, physical distancing and personal hygiene. Facilities should not allow large group visits. Special consideration may be given to end-of-life situations, palliative care and dementia units.    Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advice on residential aged care facilities also sets out that residential aged care facilities should implement the following measures for restricting visits and visitors to reduce the risk of transmission to residents, including:  -	Limiting visits to a short duration;  -	Limiting visits to a maximum of two visitors at one time per day. These may be immediate social supports (family members, close friends) or professional service or advocacy;  -	Visits should be conducted in a resident’s room, outdoors, or in a specific area designated by the RACF, rather than communal areas where the risk of transmission to residents is greater;  -	No large group visits or gatherings, including social activities or entertainment, should be permitted at this time;  -	No school groups of any size should be allowed to visit RACFs.    Visitors should also be encouraged to practise social distancing practices where possible, including maintaining a distance of 1.5 metres.    This represents a level 2G policy.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200817232607/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20200919205923/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-families-and-residents-on-restricted-visits-to-residential-aged-care-facilities    https://web.archive.org/web/20200908043448/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-advice-on-residential-aged-care-facilities

According to the CDNA national guidelines for the prevention, control and public health management of COVID-19 outbreaks in residential care facilities in Australia (published by the Department of Health of the Australia Government on 13 Mar 2020, updated on 29 July 2020), it sets out restrictions on visitors and communal activities. It suggests that during a COVID-19 outbreak visitor access into and within the facility should be limited. Details include:    Facilities should implement the following:  -	suspend all group activities, particularly those that involve visitors (e.g. musicians).  -	postpone visits from non-essential external providers (e.g. hairdressers)  -	ask regular visitors and families of residents of the COVID-19 outbreak to only visit for essential reasons. Discourage visits by young children as they are generally unable to comply with standard precautions and PPE requirements. Record the name and phone number of visitors on a register. Screen any visitors for respiratory illness.  -	instruct visitors to          - wear PPE as directed by staff          - enter and leave the facility directly without spending time in communal areas          - perform good hand hygiene before entering and after leaving the resident’s room and the facility.    Additionally, visitors must be asked about symptoms and be instructed not to enter the RCF until any symptoms have resolved. In terms of isolation, a resident with relevant symptoms should be placed in a single room with their own ensuite facilities, if possible, while waiting for a diagnosis. Where possible, residents requiring droplet precautions should be restricted to their room. Residents may attend urgent medical or procedural appointments but should wear a surgical mask if tolerated. Staff escorting residents should wear a surgical mask, gowns, eye protection and gloves in addition to observing hand hygiene    The Guide to the Establishment of an Aged Care Health Emergency Response Operations Centre (published on 20 Aug 2020) is intended to operate alongside the CDNA national guidelines for the prevention, control and public health management of COVID-19 outbreaks in residential care facilities in Australia. It sets out that restricted people movement across facilities/suburbs/borders etc.    This represents a level 2G policy.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200923100917/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia    https://web.archive.org/web/20201103023506/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/07/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20210330035524/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre    https://web.archive.org/web/20210403145049/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/08/guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre-guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre.pdf

column15: According to the Department of Health (published on 17 April 2020), it provides that practical guidance and advice have been prepared for school leaders to engage with children, parents, teachers and support staff to reduce even further the relatively low risk of Coronavirus (COVID-19) transmission in schools during the COVID-19 pandemic. It suggests physical distancing. It also states that everyone must practise good hygiene to protect against infection and prevent the spread of COVID-19. Additionally, it also states to reduce the spread of viruses or germs in schools through environmental cleaning. column51: According to the Department of Infrastructure, Transport, Regional Development and Communications (published on 29 May 2020), it states that public transport operators have continued to service the Australian community during the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic with risk mitigation and health and hygiene practices in place. column88: According to the Australian Government (published on 7 August 2020), it states that advice if people have cold or flu like symptoms, they should seek medical advice about having a test for COVID-19. Additionally, testing is even more important if people are unwell and:  -	people have recently returned to Australia from overseas. All travellers will be quarantined for 14 days on arrival into Australia;  -	people have been in close contact with someone diagnosed with COVID-19 in the past 14 days;  -	people are a health care, aged care or residential care worker or staff member with direct patient contact.    People will be able to contact their doctor to arrange a test or they can attend a respiratory clinic.    This suggests that people will likely be able to get test if they have symptoms and meet specific criteria as stated above. column115: According to the website of the Department of Health of the Australian Government (updated on 26 Jun, archived on 17 Aug), it suggests that special restrictions remain in place for aged care facilities to protect older Australians as of 15 Sep 2020. The document includes restrictions as follows.    The following people cannot enter residential aged care facilities:  -	People who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days  -	People who have been in contact with a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days  -	People who are unwell, including with a fever or symptoms of acute respiratory illness (e.g. cough, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath)  -	People who do not have an up-to-date (i.e. 2020) flu vaccination  Children of all ages can now visit RACFs. All visitors, including children, must follow any restrictions. This includes visitor numbers, physical distancing and personal hygiene. Facilities should not allow large group visits. Special consideration may be given to end-of-life situations, palliative care and dementia units.    Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advice on residential aged care facilities also sets out that residential aged care facilities should implement the following measures for restricting visits and visitors to reduce the risk of transmission to residents, including:  -	Limiting visits to a short duration;  -	Limiting visits to a maximum of two visitors at one time per day. These may be immediate social supports (family members, close friends) or professional service or advocacy;  -	Visits should be conducted in a resident’s room, outdoors, or in a specific area designated by the RACF, rather than communal areas where the risk of transmission to residents is greater;  -	No large group visits or gatherings, including social activities or entertainment, should be permitted at this time;  -	No school groups of any size should be allowed to visit RACFs.    Visitors should also be encouraged to practise social distancing practices where possible, including maintaining a distance of 1.5 metres.    This represents a level 2G policy.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200817232607/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20200919205923/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-families-and-residents-on-restricted-visits-to-residential-aged-care-facilities    https://web.archive.org/web/20200908043448/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-advice-on-residential-aged-care-facilities    Additional notes of the CDNA National Guidelines:  According to the CDNA national guidelines for the prevention, control and public health management of COVID-19 outbreaks in residential care facilities in Australia (published by the Department of Health of the Australia Government on 13 Mar 2020, updated on 29 July 2020), it sets out restrictions on visitors and communal activities. It suggests that during a COVID-19 outbreak visitor access into and within the facility should be limited. Details include:    Facilities should implement the following:  -	suspend all group activities, particularly those that involve visitors (e.g. musicians).  -	postpone visits from non-essential external providers (e.g. hairdressers)  -	ask regular visitors and families of residents of the COVID-19 outbreak to only visit for essential reasons. Discourage visits by young children as they are generally unable to comply with standard precautions and PPE requirements. Record the name and phone number of visitors on a register. Screen any visitors for respiratory illness.  -	instruct visitors to          - wear PPE as directed by staff          - enter and leave the facility directly without spending time in communal areas          - perform good hand hygiene before entering and after leaving the resident’s room and the facility.    Additionally, visitors must be asked about symptoms and be instructed not to enter the RCF until any symptoms have resolved. In terms of isolation, a resident with relevant symptoms should be placed in a single room with their own ensuite facilities, if possible, while waiting for a diagnosis. Where possible, residents requiring droplet precautions should be restricted to their room. Residents may attend urgent medical or procedural appointments but should wear a surgical mask if tolerated. Staff escorting residents should wear a surgical mask, gowns, eye protection and gloves in addition to observing hand hygiene    The Guide to the Establishment of an Aged Care Health Emergency Response Operations Centre (published on 20 Aug 2020) is intended to operate alongside the CDNA national guidelines for the prevention, control and public health management of COVID-19 outbreaks in residential care facilities in Australia. It sets out that restricted people movement across facilities/suburbs/borders etc.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20200923100917/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia    https://web.archive.org/web/20201103023506/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/07/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-prevention-control-and-public-health-management-of-covid-19-outbreaks-in-residential-care-facilities-in-australia.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20210330035524/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre    https://web.archive.org/web/20210403145049/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/08/guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre-guide-to-the-establishment-of-an-aged-care-health-emergency-response-operations-centre.pdf

This represents a continuation of the policy response of schools remaining open with COVID safe practices.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201029095044/https://www.health.gov.au/news/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc-advice-on-reducing-the-potential-risk-of-covid-19-transmission-in-schools-24-april-2020#help-stop-the-spread-and-stay-healthy
column24: As published on 23/11/2020 on the federal government's Business site ‘all restrictions and measures will be implemented in accordance with state and territory laws’ for workplace closures. Indicating that workplace closure are enforced at a state and territory level on 15/12/2020, representing a continuation of the policy response of workplace closures at a national level https://web.archive.org/web/20201201144307/https://www.business.gov.au/risk-management/emergency-management/coronavirus-information-and-support-for-business/restrictions-on-non-essential-services
column33: As published on the Federal Government’s Department of Health’s website last updated on 26/05/2020 state and territory governments have different restrictions in place on public events. There is no national policy on 15/12/2020 and this represents a continuation of the policy response. Archived link provides state and territory restrictions. https://web.archive.org/web/20201201141832/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19
column42: As published on the Federal Government’s Department of Health’s website last updated on 26/05/2020 state and territory governments have different restrictions in place on public gatherings. There is no national policy on 15/12/2020 and this represents a continuation of the policy response. Archived link provides state and territory restrictions. https://web.archive.org/web/20201201141832/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19
column51: Public transport closures and requirements are under the responsibilities of local jurisdictions, however, the Department of Infrastructure, Transport, Regional Development and Communications released a document outlining ‘the Principles for Covid-19 Public Transport Operations’ on 19/05/2020. This document provides advice for commuters and operators for COVID safe environment on public transport such as providing contactless facilities, reducing transport lengths and regular transport sanitisation. This represents a continuation of the policy prior https://web.archive.org/web/20210712064038/https://www.infrastructure.gov.au/transport/files/COVID19_public_transport_principles_29052020.pdf
column60: As published on the Federal Government’s Department of Health’s website last updated on 26/05/2020 state and territory governments have different restrictions in place on public gatherings and the national government encourages social distancing and good hygiene practice whilst in public. This represents a continuation of the policy response with no national stay at home requirement.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201201141832/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/limits-on-public-gatherings-for-coronavirus-covid-19
column69: As updated on 26/06/2020 the Department of Health released the ‘3-step Framework for a COVIDSafe Australia’ which outlines that the public should refer to state and territory governments for border and internal movement restrictions. This policy is a continuation of the policy prior and in place on 15/12/2020. https://web.archive.org/web/20210118144251/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/3-step-framework-for-a-covidsafe-australia
column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, no foreign arrivals are permitted into the country unless they are in an exempt category or have been granted an individual exemption which includes compassionate and national interest grounds. All international arrivals must quarantine for 14 days at a designated facility. There is the possibility to travel to Australia quarantine free without an exemption if you have been in New Zealand for 14 days or more and not been in a designated COVID-19 outbreak location, and you are travelling to Australia on a quarantine-free flight from 16/10/2020. This policy is a continuation of the policy prior and in place on 15/12/2020.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201130233418/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20201130222312/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/new-zealand-safe-travel-zone
column77: Individuals are able to receive a $250 coronavirus supplement per fortnight until 31/12/2020. The temporary coronavirus supplement will be reduced to $150 per fortnight starting from 01/01/2021. Individuals from all states/territories except Northern Territory can receive a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment of $1500 for each 14 day period someone self-isolate, quarantine or care for a person who has COVID-19 through Centrelink as published on the Services Australia website last updated on 12/12/2020.   https://web.archive.org/web/20201201112209/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/services/centrelink/coronavirus-supplement  https://web.archive.org/web/20201219194817/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/individuals/services/centrelink/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment
column79: No national policies related to any types of debt and contract relief were established. However, on 27/03/2020, the Australian Energy Regulator published the "Statement of Expectations of energy businesses", which sets out reasonable expectations set reasonable expectations of energy companies to protect householders during the COVID-19 pandemic until 31/03/2021.   https://web.archive.org/web/20201205123414/https://www.energy.gov.au/covid-19-information/support-australian-households
column86: A range of public health campaigns remain in place across broad government online media platforms including the Department of Health, which provides a list of resources about COVID-19, including fact sheets, guidelines and other publications. This represents a continuation of the policy prior.   https://web.archive.org/web/20201212084722/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/collections/coronavirus-covid-19-campaign-resources  https://web.archive.org/web/20201123144502/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-resources
column88: The national policy for testing is that anyone exhibiting cold or flu-like symptoms should get tested. However, "‘As the situation changes, states and territories may adjust their testing criteria based on local needs.", as published on the Australian government’s Department of Health’s website and last updated on 16/10/2020 and currently in place. This policy represents a continuation of the policy prior.   https://web.archive.org/web/20201201162606/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/what-you-need-to-know-about-coronavirus-covid-19#how-to-get-tested
column90: There is no national contact tracing policy at the moment and is delegated to state and territory jurisdictions. Specifically, the Department of Health published the "National Contact Tracing Review" which is a review of COVID-19 contact tracing and outbreak management systems and processes in all states and territories. Also notably, the Australian national government released a voluntary COVIDSafe app that uses Bluetooth to track contacts, but debates surround its effectiveness.  This represents a continuation of the policy prior.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201201201431/https://covidsafe.gov.au/  https://web.archive.org/web/20201201204038/https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/national-contact-tracing-review
column103: As published on the Department of Health website, updated on 18/11/2020, there is no national requirement on face masks, however, ‘where there is significant community transmission (as determined by jurisdictional public health authorities), you may choose, or be required to, wear a mask. If physical distance is difficult to maintain, for example on public transport, covering your face with a mask can provide some extra protection’. Face masks requirements are imposed at state and territory levels which can be found in archived link.  https://web.archive.org/web/20201123160245/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/how-to-protect-yourself-and-others-from-coronavirus-covid-19/masks
column106: There are no vaccines available in Australia until 22/02/2021  https://web.archive.org/web/20210218072330/https://www.health.gov.au/news/covid-19-vaccine-rollout-on-track-to-begin-22-february
column115: Notes  As published on the Department of Health’s website, aged care visits and COVID restrictions are delegated at state and territory jurisdictions which depends on each state/territory's case numbers. There are recommendations for aged care facility protections as such in the National COVID-19 aged care plan. This represents a continuation of the policy prior.   https://web.archive.org/web/20210215191906/https://www.health.gov.au/health-topics/aged-care/advice-on-aged-care-during-covid-19.advice-for-the-aged-care-sector
